bought his first birds from ostrich-farming monks in Oklahoma City.
   Two years later, the Sticklers moved their 10,000 head of cattle
out and moved the birds in - about 175 of them now. The brothers
have sold more than 300 chicks nationwide. Prices range from $500
to $3,000 per chick.
   ``You just feed 'em, water 'em and leave 'em alone,'' he said.
``With cattle you worked from dark to dark. Back home it takes 30
minutes to do the ostrich chores.''
   Stickler said that according to the American Ostrich
Association, there are more than 5,000 ostriches being bred across
the country. The association predicts an ostrich population boom of
75,000 to 100,000 by mid-1990.
