<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven sculptures in a city park are anyone's for
the asking _if they can lug them away.
   The weighty pieces of art that turned a downtown lot into
Sculpture Park have to be moved to make way for development, say
owners of the land.
   ``We've got these two-ton canaries to dispose of,'' said Suzanne
Clarke McDonough, a leader of Sculpture Chicago, a non-profit
group. ``It's no joke.''
   The sculptures are made of steel plates and chains and other
heavy materials. Artists have taken all the sculptures but seven.
One will go on a long-term loan and six with no strings attached.
   ``We have to have the site cleared by mid-September, or I'm
afraid ... they could be demolished,'' Ms. McDonough said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Oklahoma ranchers say their Nebraska
counterparts should get their heads out of the sand, and join their
boom industry _ raising ostriches.
   Mike and Doug Stickler told farmers at the Nebraska State Fair
they dropped out of the cattle feeding business three years ago to
concentrate on ostriches, those big, long-necked birds who can
gallop at 45 mph for 30 minutes and can kill you with a swipe of a
foot.
   The family bought three breeding females and a male. This year,
they got 102 eggs and 75 percent of them have made it to the
yearling stage. Yearling pairs can fetch up to $15,000, Doug
Stickler says. Chicks sell for about $1,500 apiece.
   Their leather, which stretches to 12 to 15 square feet, brings
$25 a square foot or higher, depending on quality. A full set of
feathers fetches about $200. Their meat brings about $7 a pound and
ostrich jerky sells for about $17 a pound. Even their eggshells
sell for $35 to $50 each.
   ``We tell farmers that this is a good alternative to wheat,
cattle and corn,'' Doug Stickler said. ``Farmers are bullheaded and
don't want to quit farming. This has been an excellent business for
us.''
