<LEADPARA>  A San Jose man who federal agents say hatched a large ostrich egg caper was
arrested Thursday morning by U.S. Customs officers, a few hours before he was
allegedly due to fly out of the country on business.;    Dimitris Chaniotis,
owner of a family construction firm and of a business called "Ostrich
Wholesale Resource" on Park Avenue, was arraigned later in the day before U.S.
Magistrate Patricia Trumbull.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AGENTS ARREST OSTRICH EXPORTER  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Chaniotis was charged in a complaint issued in San Diego on Wednesday with
smuggling, aiding and abetting smuggling, and illegally importing wildlife
into the United States, according to U.S. Attorney Michael Wheat.;    San Jose
agent Matt Van Dyke called the 34-year-old Chaniotis an "orchestrator" of an
operation designed to bring valuable live ostriches and their eggs into the
United States from South Africa.;    The arrest of Chaniotis followed two
raids last week on a farm in the Almaden Valley area of San Jose, where
officers said they seized 300 eggs -- with a total value of more than $300,000
-- in addition to four ostrich chicks and five six-foot-tall adult birds.;   
The importation of foreign-raised eggs is banned by the federal government
because they can carry contagious and lethal Newcastle's disease, which,
according to Wheat, can devastate the native poultry industry.;    Chaniotis
told officers he had been involved in the legitimate ostrich business for more
than two years, exporting eggs to various countries from breeding grounds in
South Africa and Botswana, according to Van Dyke.;    Ostrich importing is
said to be a lucrative enterprise, with unhatched fertilized eggs selling for
more than $1,000 each, newborn chicks bringing as much as $4,000, and a
full-grown pair of mating ostriches commanding a price of $100,000.;    The
government began investigating Chaniotis and the Almaden Valley home where
last week's seizures were made after an alleged confederate -- Roger Jacobson
-- was arrested last October while trying to cross the Mexican border at San
Ysidro with a truckload of eggs.;    According to court documents, Jacobson
told officials Chaniotis had hired him to transport the eggs but instructed
him not to disclose the cargo to border officials. Chaniotis allegedly told
him that even if the contraband were discovered, officials would simply
confiscate the eggs and there would be "no criminal problem.";    If
convicted, Chaniotis could spend five years in prison and be fined up to
$250,000 for each charge, said Deputy U.S. Atty. Robert Crowe, of San Jose.;  
 The investigation is continuing, said Wheat.  </TEXT>
