<HEAD>Federal Wildlife Officials to Split Whooping Crane Colony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAUREL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildlife officials plan to split the world's
only captive colony of whooping cranes in November to reduce the
chance the flock could be wiped out by disease or natural disaster.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service said 22 of the 54 birds at
the Patuxent Wildlife Research Center would be shipped to the
International Crane Foundation in Baraboo, Wis. Whooping cranes are
an endangered species.
   ``The service has been concerned about having all of their eggs
in one basket, literally,'' said David Trauger, the center's deputy
director. ``The service felt it was the prudent thing to do, to
separate the breeding flocks, and there's enough breeders now to do
that.''
   The center started in 1987 to breed the birds, known for their
elaborate courtship dance, under a joint program with Canadian
wildlife officials.
   The foundation was selected as the home of the new flock after
considering several groups around the nation. Although it has not
bred whooping cranes, it has successfully bred 13 of the 14 other
crane species.
   Scientists hope that by successfully breeding whooping cranes in
captivity, they will be able to establish another flock in the
wild. An attempt to do that failed in 1975 when a flock at the
Grays Lake National Wildlife Refuge in Idaho failed to produce
enough eggs to sustain the colony.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Imported Ticks Can Pose Threat to Florida Herds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An African tick brought to the
Caribbean by accident poses a threat to Florida's cattle, sheep,
goat and white-tailed deer, say state veterinary scientists who are
trying to develop a vaccine.
   The ticks can cause a skin condition or heartwater disease that
can kill up to 90 percent of infected animals, University of
Florida scientists say.
   ``If the disease spreads to Florida, we probably would have to
quarantine the whole state. That would be devastating,'' said Dan
Childs, vice chairman of the National Cattlemen's Association
Animal Health Committee.
   Bont ticks, which infest exotic animals such as rhinoceroses and
ostriches. A shipment of rhinoceroses arriving in Texas five years
ago carried them, and the U.S. Department of Agriculture issued a
warning in June after African ticks were found on shipments of
imported ostriches sent to several U.S. cities.
   If nothing is done to control the tick in the Caribbean, it's
only a matter of time before birds or imported animals carry it to
Cuba, Jamaica, Trinidad and the United States, said Michael
Burridge, head of the university's Center for Tropical Animal
Health and its Department of Infectious Diseases.
   The ticks can carry a rickettsial bacteria that causes
heartwater disease, which is no threat to humans but causes high
fever and nervous system disorders in animals. Animals often suffer
swelling of the lungs, called pulmonary edema, and
hydropericardium, or water around the heart.
   Florida is one of the top 10 cattle-producing states, said
Childs.
   A team in Zimbabwean has produced a laboratory technique to grow
large quantities of the rickettsial bacteria in culture, but
diagnostic field tests are thought to be some three years away,
Burridge said.
   And a heartwater vaccine would not protect animals from the
associated fatal skin ailment, acute bovine dermatophilosis, which
causes sections of the animal's hide to slough off. Although rare,
the skin disease can affect humans.
   ``It's a horrible disease and we found ... that, for some
reason, it occurs only in the areas where there are tropical bont
ticks,'' Burridge said.
   ``If these ticks should spread to the United States, we're in
big trouble because the organism that causes the skin disease is in
the soil here already, just waiting for this tick to arrive,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
