<DESCRIPT>  ARTS; UNUSUAL; SHOW; SALE; PALO-ALTO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  In the fragile world of egg artistry, a simple painted egg with a bunny on it
is as Gumby to Michelangelo's David.;    Instead, think of panoramic forest
scenes inside eggshells. Think eggshell necklaces with intricate filigree
cut-outs. Think hinged, revolving music boxes.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  The Weekly, Part 2  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ARTIST CRACKS EXOTIC WORLD OF EGG DECOR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article
Also ran in EAST6, EX1/1 EX3/6  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But don't think everyday hen eggs -- they break too easily. Instead, egg
artists like Carlene Voss of Union City use ostrich eggs, goose eggs, emu
eggs, rhea eggs, mallard eggs.;    The largest one she owns is a hefty green,
pebbly cassowary egg. "The cassowary (from Australia) is the meanest bird in
captivity," Voss notes. "It stomps on its egg after it lays it." That probably
explains the cost of eggs that are saved -- $150. Voss' tiniest egg is a snail
egg, so minuscule that she keeps it in a gelatin capsule. She buys some eggs
from local ranchers and pet store owners, others she orders by mail.;    Voss'
most elaborate project started as an ostrich egg and ended as a mauve and
burgundy carrousel that turns while music plays. Glittering with crystals, the
carrousel retails at $425. Another is a black-and-white clown, fashioned from
an emu egg, that took first prize at the Alameda County Fair.;    These are a
far cry from the first eggs Voss decorated with dried flowers and rickrack
eight years ago. When her daughter Shawnie, then 9, broke her elbow in a
gymnastics accident, doctors advised activities to keep her hand busy. The two
of them decorated eggs together. When Carlene sold her first eggs for $2, she
was thrilled.;    Shawnie, a senior at Logan High School, long since moved on
to other activities. But Carlene has taken lessons from Dorothy Husokowski of
Hayward for five years. She has refined her skills and upgraded her equipment.
She suits up like a welder with her jeweler's glasses and floorboards the
pedal of her Dremel hobby drill -- hrrghmmmmmm -- to precision-cut an egg.
Voss' work now sells from $22 up and is available at the Gift Gallery in
Fremont.;    There are 88 eggers -- as the artists are known -- in the
Northern California Egg Artists and perhaps 2,000 in the United States.;   
Eggers never rest. There's the Egger's Journal to read, more decorating
lessons to take and, for the second year, the Decorated Egg Show and Sale in
Palo Alto. Last year the Northern California Egg Artists contributed $3,000 to
the Make-A-Wish Foundation This year's event, which also benefits Make-A-Wish,
will feature 88 tables. Egg decorating workshops will be available, from $20
up, depending on the size of the egg and materials provided.;    The
egg-decorating tradition is a noble one, stretching back in history. Ancient
people, who saw eggs as a source of life, decorated them in celebration of sun
and spring. Goldsmith Peter Carl Faberge created legendary jeweled eggs for
the courts of Czars Alexander III and Nicholas II.;    Voss' cupboards teem
with Lilliputian supplies. Bins and clear plastic boxes store the stuff of
miniaturists' dreams: toy soldiers; itty bitty mice, squirrels and teddy
bears; inch-long locomotives; bristly green trees. There are yards of faux
pearls; racks of tweezers, pliers and epoxy-mixing sticks; drawers of
gold-colored stands and Corian pedestals. Diamond dust (glitter made from
low-grade diamonds) sometimes sprinkles the sandwiches in the Voss household.;
   Once Voss starts on an egg, she'll work right through till 3 in the
morning, if necessary. "Everyone needs a niche," she says. "When I found eggs,
I found my niche."; IF YOU'RE INTERESTED; The Decorated Egg Show and Sale
sponsored by Northern California Egg Artists will be held Saturday and Sunday
at Hyatt Rickeys, 4219 El Camino Real, Palo Alto. Admission is $8 for
pre-registered guests, from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. both days and is $3.50 for the
general public from noon to 5 p.m. both days. For information, call or (415)
935-2594. Proceeds benefit Make-A-Wish Foundation.  </TEXT>
