<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Exotic Animals</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DELPHOS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a flock of Canada geese fly northward on
their annual spring migration, their honking cries arouse dozens of
their kind held in wire cages and orange crates under a tent at a
western Ohio auction.
   The tent also shelters badgers, wood ducks, black bears, swans,
foxes, prairie dogs, cougars and a large female lion, who growls
when someone gets too close.
   Beyond, in several newly built stalls and pens, is a veritable
Noah's ark of animals from all parts of the globe with
foreign-sounding names such as aoudad, binturong, colobus, emu,
ibex, guanacos, muntjac, oryx, rhea, watusi and zebu.
   Within hours, the fate of all will be set by an auctioneer's
gavel, their destinations determined by the highest bidder.
   Woods &amp; Waters Auction, held twice a year on the outskirts of
this quiet little farm town, bills itself as the largest animal
auction east of the Mississippi River.
   At its three-day sale in April, up to 8,000 animals, including
birds and reptiles were sold to breeders, animal dealers, owners of
game ranches, meat dealers and hobbyists with a penchant for a
particular species, says Woods &amp; Waters' owner Dick Osting.
   For the most part, the customers were a reticent lot who shunned
publicity and people trying to photograph animals were escorted off
the premises by a security guard.
   Osting complains that the media have ``distorted'' their
business by only photographing animals that are injured, kept in
undersized cages or left in pens without food and water.
   ``The media want to stir up a story...to shock readers,'' says
Osting, 37, who's operated the family-run auction for five years.
``The only thing the media do when they print this gory stuff is to
upset the humane society and the government, which is two people we
don't want upset at us.''
   Osting says auctions help the wild and exotic animal industry
because they bring the business of buying and selling animals out
into public view.
   ``The intention of the auction is to clean up the business,'' he
says. ``We're stepping out into the open, inviting regulation.
We're saying, `As long as you don't regulate us out of the
business, regulate us.'''
   Animal welfare people contend there are abuses. Anne Maroukis,
co-founder of Guardians of the Earth, an Ohio-based animal welfare
rights group, says some cages were inadequate, as in the case of
three bear cubs brought to the auction in a cardboard box, or too
small. An adult black bear, she says, had cuts above his eyes from
hitting his head against exposed metal edges when he'd try to
stand, and some cages lacked food and water.
   Osting says some injuries do occur in the transport of animals
to the auction. He adds, ``I've heard about foxes in too small a
cage. He's at a three-day auction. He probably just came from real
nice facilities and he'll probably go back to real nice facilities.
After all, the animal is here for just three days. I think they
make way too big an issue of it.''
   Maroukis says, ``We've tried to work with the Department of
Agriculture. They keep saying they have no jurisdiction, but if
they don't, who does?''
   Don Castner, an inspector with the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, says he saw some injuries, but none appeared
life-threatening.
   Auctions are not regulated by the federal government, so
inspectors for the USDA, which oversees the transportation of
animals, can only cite dealers or breeders whose animals appear to
have been injured in transit, he says. The USDA has no control over
privately owned animals.
   When asked about a flock of ostrich-like birds called rheas with
bloodied legs, which Osting said probably were injured during
transport, Castner replied that the USDA also doesn't regulate
birds or reptiles.
   ``We can't do what we can't do. We only regulate the
transportation of animals owned by dealers. That's it.''
</TEXT>
